SIMPLE: purser
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Purser
<hw>Purs"er</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Purse</er>,
and cf. <er>Bursar</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A commissioned officer in the
navy who had charge of the provisions, clothing, and public moneys on
shipboard; -- now called <altname>paymaster</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A clerk on steam passenger vessels whose duty it is
to keep the accounts of the vessels, such as the receipt of freight,
tickets, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Colloquially, any paymaster or cashier.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Purser's name</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>a false
name.</cd> <mark>[Slang]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pursership</ent>⟦br⟧
